# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: french-ironclad-normandie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] Antony Preston was born in 1938 in Salford, Lancashire, son of the 16th Viscount Gormanston and Miss Julia O'Mahony.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] After becoming a wartime evacuee, he was educated in South Africa at King Edward VII School, Johannesburg, and the University of Witwatersrand.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] On his return to England he spent some years at the National Maritime Museum, Greenwich, before becoming Editor of the periodical *Defence*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] During the 1970s he was employed by a specialist publisher, Conway Maritime Press, as editor of their *Warship* annual.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] He also produced the specialised newsletter *Navint*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] In the early nineties, he took over as chief editor of the magazine *Naval Forces* at the German editorial group Mönch.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] He left to resume as editor of *Warships* in 1996.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] Antony Preston lived in London until his death in 2004.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/antony-preston] His son Matt Preston (born 1961 and the eldest of Preston's four children) has gained celebrity as a TV judge on *MasterChef Australia* and as a restaurant critic-columnist for the Melbourne Age & Herald-Sun newspapers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] A **frigate** (/ˈfrɪɡɪt/) is a type of warship.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In different eras, the roles and capabilities of ships classified as frigates have varied.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th to early 18th centuries the term "frigate" was loosely given to any full-rigged ship built for speed and manoeuvrability and intended for scouting, escort or patrol.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] By the second quarter of the 18th century, what is regarded as the "true frigate" was developed in France and subsequently copied by other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This type of vessel was characterised by a long sleek design with a single gun deck of 28 and 36 cannons, and an unarmed deck below used for berthing the crew.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the mid-nineteenth century the definition of *frigate* was expanded to include the early ironclad warships, which also had a single gun deck.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] However, later developments in ironclad ships rendered the designation obsolete and the term fell out of favour in navies worldwide.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The term was reintroduced in the Second World War to describe a seagoing escort ship of intermediate size between a corvette and a destroyer.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] After the war, this definition has gradually expanded to include many different kinds of vessels, from large ocean-going anti-submarine warfare ships to corvettes, destroyers, and nuclear-powered guided-missile cruisers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The etymology of the word (Italian: *fregata*; Dutch: *fregat*; Spanish/Catalan/Portuguese/Sicilian: *fragata*; French: *frégate*; German: *Fregatte*) remains uncertain, although it may have originated as a corruption of *aphractus*, a Latin word for an open vessel with no lower deck.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] *Aphractus*, in turn, derived from the Ancient Greek phrase ἄφρακτος ναῦς (*aphraktos naus*) – "undefended ship".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The term *frigate* originated in the Mediterranean in the late 16th century, referring to a lighter galley-type warship with oars, sails and a light armament, built for speed and manoeuvrability.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first recorded usage of the term seems to date from 1562, when Alonso Pérez, Duke of Medina Sidonia armed a galley fleet complemented with vessels called *fragatas* which were claimed to be invented by him.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These frigates proved impractical and were retired soon.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Other sources state Medina Sidonia actually credited Álvaro de Bazán, Marquis of Santa Cruz with their invention.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The term was later used as an alternate name for the *galizabra*, a kind of galleass built by Álvaro's brother Alonso in 1584 as a cross between a galley and a zabra.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1583, during the Eighty Years' War of 1568–1648, Habsburg Spain recovered the southern Netherlands from the Protestant rebels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This soon resulted in the use of the occupied ports as bases for privateers, the "Dunkirkers", to attack the shipping of the Dutch and their allies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] To achieve this the Dunkirkers developed small, manoeuvrable, sailing vessels that came to be referred to as frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In French, the term *frigate* gave rise to a verb – *frégater*, meaning 'to build long and low', and to an adjective, adding more confusion.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Even the huge English *Sovereign of the Seas* could be described as "a delicate frigate" by a contemporary after her upper decks were reduced in 1651.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The navy of the Dutch Republic became the first navy to build the larger ocean-going frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Dutch navy had three principal tasks in the struggle against Spain: to protect Dutch merchant ships at sea, to blockade the ports of Spanish-held Flanders to damage trade and halt enemy privateering, and to fight the Spanish fleet and prevent troop landings.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first two tasks required speed, shallowness of draft for the shallow waters around the Netherlands, and the ability to carry sufficient supplies to maintain a blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The third task required heavy armament, sufficient to stand up to the Spanish fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first of the larger battle-capable frigates were built around 1600 at Hoorn in Holland.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] By the later stages of the Eighty Years' War (1568–1648) the Dutch had switched entirely from the heavier ships still used by the English and Spanish to the lighter frigates, carrying around 40 guns and weighing around 300 tons.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th century, the term *fregat* in the Dutch Navy described any oceangoing warship carrying fewer than 40 guns.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The effectiveness of the Dutch frigates became most evident in the Battle of the Downs in 1639, encouraging most other navies, especially the English, to adopt similar designs.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The fleets built by the Commonwealth of England in the 1650s generally consisted of ships described as "frigates", the largest of which were two-decker "great frigates" of the third rate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Carrying 60 guns, these vessels were as big and capable as "great ships" of the time; however, most other frigates at the time were used as "cruisers": independent fast ships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" implied a long hull-design, which relates directly to speed (see hull speed) and which also, in turn, helped the development of the broadside tactic in naval warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th century the term 'frigate' was sometimes applied very loosely and could be used for any warship.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] At this time, a further design evolved, reintroducing oars and resulting in galley frigates such as HMS *Charles Galley* of 1676, which was rated as a 32-gun fifth-rate but also had a bank of 40 oars set below the upper deck that could propel the ship in the absence of a favourable wind.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In Danish, the word "fregat" often applied to warships carrying as few as 16 guns, such as HMS *Falcon*, which the British classified as a sloop.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Under the rating system of the Royal Navy, by the middle of the 18th century, the term "frigate" was technically restricted to single-decked ships of the fifth rate, though small 28-gun frigates were classed as sixth rate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The classic sailing frigate, or "true frigate", well-known today for its role in the Napoleonic Wars, can be traced back to French developments in the second quarter of the 18th century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The French-built *Médée* of 1740 is often regarded as the first example of this type.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These ships were square-rigged and carried all their main guns on a single continuous upper deck.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The lower deck, known as the "gun deck", now carried no armament, and functioned as a "berth deck" where the crew lived, and was in fact placed below the waterline of the new frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The typical earlier cruiser had a partially armed lower deck, from which it was known as a "half-battery" or *demi-batterie* ship.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Removing the guns from this deck allowed the height of the hull upperworks to be lowered, giving the resulting "true-frigate" much improved sailing qualities.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy captured a number of the new French frigates, including *Médée*, during the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–1748) and the British were impressed by them, particularly for their inshore handling capabilities.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] They soon built copies (ordered in 1747), based on a French privateer named *Tygre*, and started to adapt the type to their own needs, setting the standard for other frigates as the leading naval power.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] However, most ships of this size were called "ship sloops".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] A total of fifty-nine French sailing frigates were built between 1777 and 1790, with a standard design averaging a hull length of 135 ft (41 m) and an average draught of 13 ft (4.0 m).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The new frigates recorded sailing speeds of up to 14 knots (26 km/h; 16 mph), significantly faster than their predecessor vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1778, the British Admiralty introduced a larger "heavy" frigate, with a main battery of twenty-six or twenty-eight 18-pounder guns (with smaller guns carried on the quarterdeck and forecastle).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This move may reflect the naval conditions at the time; with both France and Spain as enemies, the usual British preponderance in ship numbers was no longer the case and there was pressure on the British to produce cruisers of individually greater force.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In reply, the first French 18-pounder frigates were laid down in 1781.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The 18-pounder frigate eventually became the standard frigate of the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The British produced larger, 38-gun, and slightly smaller, 36-gun, versions and also a 32-gun design that can be considered an 'economy version'.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The 32-gun frigates also had the advantage that they could be built by the many smaller, less-specialised shipbuilders.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates could (and usually did) additionally carry smaller carriage-mounted guns on their quarterdecks and forecastles (the superstructures above the upper deck).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1778 the Carron Iron Company of Scotland produced a naval gun which would revolutionise the armament of smaller naval vessels, including the frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The carronade was a large calibre, short-barrelled naval cannon which was light, quick to reload and needed a smaller crew than a conventional long gun.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Due to its lightness it could be mounted on the forecastle and quarterdeck of frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] It greatly increased the firepower, measured in weight of metal (the combined weight of all projectiles fired in one broadside), of these vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The disadvantages of the carronade were that it had a much shorter range and was less accurate than a long gun.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The British quickly saw the advantages of the new weapon and soon employed it on a wide scale.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The US Navy also copied the design soon after its appearance.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The French and other nations eventually adopted variations of the weapon in succeeding decades.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The typical heavy frigate had a main armament of 18-pounder long guns, plus 32-pounder carronades mounted on its upper decks.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first "super-heavy frigates", armed with 24-pounder long guns, were built by the naval architect F H Chapman for the Swedish navy in 1782.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Because of a shortage of ships-of-the-line, the Swedes wanted these frigates, the *Bellona* class, to be able to stand in the battle line in an emergency.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] It is not known whether the French were seeking to produce very potent cruisers or merely to address stability problems in old ships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The British, alarmed by the prospect of these powerful heavy frigates, responded by rasée-ing three of their smaller 64-gun battleships, including *Indefatigable*, which went on to have a very successful career as a frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] At this time the British also built a few 24-pounder-armed large frigates, the most successful of which was HMS *Endymion* (1,277 tons).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1797, three of the United States Navy's first six major ships were rated as 44-gun frigates, which operationally carried fifty-six to sixty 24-pounder long guns and 32-pounder or 42-pounder carronades on two decks; they were exceptionally powerful.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] USS *Constitution*, preserved as a museum ship by the US Navy, is the oldest commissioned warship afloat, and is a surviving example of a frigate from the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] *Constitution* and her sister ships *President* and *United States* were created in a response to deal with the Barbary Coast pirates and in conjunction with the Naval Act of 1794.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Joshua Humphreys proposed that only live oak, a tree that grew only in America, should be used to build these ships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Admiralty, concerned by repeated defeats in single-ship actions, responded to the success of the American 44s in three ways.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] They built a class of conventional 40-gun, 24-pounder armed frigates on the lines of *Endymion*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] They cut down three old 74-gun Ships-of-the-Line into *rasées*, producing frigates with a 32-pounder main armament, supplemented by 42-pounder carronades.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These had an armament that far exceeded the power of the American ships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Finally, *Leander* and *Newcastle*, 1,500-ton spar-decked frigates (with an enclosed waist, giving a continuous line of guns from bow to stern at the level of the quarterdeck/forecastle), were built, which were an almost exact match in size and firepower to the American 44-gun frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were perhaps the hardest-worked of warship types during the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] While smaller than a ship-of-the-line, they were formidable opponents for the large numbers of sloops and gunboats, not to mention privateers or merchantmen.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Able to carry six months' stores, they had very long range; and vessels larger than frigates were considered too valuable to operate independently.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates scouted for the fleet, went on commerce-raiding missions and patrols, and conveyed messages and dignitaries.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Usually, frigates would fight in small numbers or singly against other frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] They would avoid contact with ships-of-the-line; even in the midst of a fleet engagement it was bad etiquette for a ship of the line to fire on an enemy frigate which had not fired first.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were involved in fleet battles, often as "repeating frigates".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the smoke and confusion of battle, signals made by the fleet commander, whose flagship might be in the thick of the fighting, might be missed by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were therefore stationed to windward or leeward of the main line of battle, and had to maintain a clear line of sight to the commander's flagship.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Signals from the flagship were then repeated by the frigates, which themselves standing out of the line and clear from the smoke and disorder of battle, could be more easily seen by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] If damage or loss of masts prevented the flagship from making clear conventional signals, the repeating frigates could interpret them and hoist their own in the correct manner, passing on the commander's instructions clearly.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] For officers in the Royal Navy, a frigate was a desirable posting.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates often saw action, which meant a greater chance of glory, promotion, and prize money.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Unlike larger ships that were placed in ordinary, frigates were kept in service in peacetime as a cost-saving measure and to provide experience to frigate captains and officers which would be useful in wartime.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates could also carry marines for boarding enemy ships or for operations on shore; in 1832, the frigate USS *Potomac* landed a party of 282 sailors and Marines ashore in the US Navy's first Sumatran expedition.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates remained a crucial element of navies until the mid-19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first ironclads were classified as "frigates" because of the number of guns they carried.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] However, terminology changed as iron and steam became the norm, and the role of the frigate was assumed first by the protected cruiser and then by the light cruiser.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates are often the vessel of choice in historical naval novels due to their relative freedom compared to ships-of-the-line (kept for fleet actions) and smaller vessels (generally assigned to a home port and less widely ranging).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] For example, the Patrick O'Brian Aubrey–Maturin series, C.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Forester's Horatio Hornblower series and Alexander Kent's Richard Bolitho series.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The 2003 film *Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World* features a reconstructed historic frigate, HMS *Rose*, to depict Aubrey's frigate HMS *Surprise*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Vessels classed as frigates continued to play a great role in navies with the adoption of steam power in the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 1830s, navies experimented with large paddle steamers equipped with large guns mounted on one deck, which were termed "paddle frigates".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] From the mid-1840s on, frigates which more closely resembled the traditional sailing frigate were built with steam engines and screw propellers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These "screw frigates", built first of wood and later of iron, continued to perform the traditional role of the frigate until late in the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] From 1859, armour was added to ships based on existing frigate and ship of the line designs.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The additional weight of the armour on these first ironclad warships meant that they could have only one gun deck, and they were technically frigates, even though they were more powerful than existing ships-of-the-line and occupied the same strategic role.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The phrase "armoured frigate" remained in use for some time to denote a sail-equipped, broadside-firing type of ironclad.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first such ship was the revolutionary Marine Nationale wooden-hulled *Gloire*, protected by 12 cm-thick (4.7 in) armour plates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The British response was HMS *Warrior* of the Warrior-class ironclads, launched in 1860.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] With her iron hull, steam engines propelling the 9,137 ton vessel to speeds of up to 14 knots and rifled breechloading 110-pdr guns, *Warrior* is the ancestor of all modern warships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] During the 1880s, as warship design shifted from iron to steel and cruising warships without sails started to appear, the term "frigate" fell out of use.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Vessels with armoured sides were designated as "battleships" or "armoured cruisers", while "protected cruisers" only possessed an armoured deck, and unarmoured vessels, including frigates and sloops, were classified as "unprotected cruisers".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Modern frigates are related to earlier frigates only by name.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" was readopted during the Second World War by the British Royal Navy to describe an anti-submarine escort vessel that was larger than a corvette (based on a mercantile design), while smaller than a destroyer.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The vessels were originally to be termed "twin screw corvettes" until the Royal Canadian Navy suggested to the British re-introducing the term "frigate" for the significantly enlarged vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates, termed destroyer escorts by the US at the time, are less expensive to build and maintain than larger destroyers and cruisers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] 22 of these were reclassified as frigates after the war, as were the remaining 24 smaller Castle-class corvettes.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate was introduced to remedy some of the shortcomings inherent in the Flower-class corvette design: limited armament, a hull form not suited to open-ocean work, a single shaft which limited speed and manoeuvrability, and a lack of range.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate was designed and built to the same mercantile construction standards (scantlings) as the corvette, allowing manufacture by yards unused to warship construction.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The first frigates of the River class (1941) were essentially two sets of corvette machinery in one larger hull, armed with the latest Hedgehog anti-submarine weapon.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate possessed less offensive firepower and speed than a destroyer, including an escort destroyer, but such qualities were not required for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Submarines were slow while submerged, and ASDIC sets did not operate effectively at speeds of over 20 knots (23 mph; 37 km/h).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Rather, the frigate was an austere and weatherly vessel suitable for mass-construction and fitted with the latest innovations in anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] As the frigate was intended purely for convoy duties, and not to deploy with the fleet, it had limited range and speed.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] It was not until the Royal Navy's Bay class of 1944 that a British design classified as a "frigate" was produced for fleet use, although it still suffered from limited speed.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These anti-aircraft frigates, built on incomplete Loch-class frigate hulls, were similar to the United States Navy's destroyer escorts (DE), although the latter had greater speed and offensive armament to better suit them to fleet deployments.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The destroyer escort concept came from design studies by the General Board of the United States Navy in 1940, as modified by requirements established by a British commission in 1941 prior to the American entry into the war, for deep-water escorts.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The American-built destroyer escorts serving in the Royal Navy were rated as Captain-class frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy's two Canadian-built *Asheville*-class and 96 British-influenced, American-built *Tacoma*-class frigates that followed originally were classified as "patrol gunboats" (PG) in the U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy but on 15 April 1943 were all reclassified as **patrol frigates (PF)**.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The introduction of the surface-to-air missile after World War II made relatively small ships effective for anti-aircraft warfare: the "guided-missile frigate".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the US navy, these vessels were called "ocean escorts" and designated "DE" or "DEG" until 1975 – a holdover from the World War II destroyer escort or "DE".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] While the Royal Navy used similar designations for their warships built in the 1950s, they maintained the use of the term "frigate"; in the 1990s the RCN re-introduced the frigate designation.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Likewise, the French Navy refers to missile-equipped ships, up to cruiser-sized ships (*Suffren*, *Tourville*, and Horizon classes), by the name of "frégate", while smaller units are named *aviso*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Soviet Navy used the term "guard-ship" (*сторожевой корабль*).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] From the 1950s to the 1970s, the United States Navy commissioned ships classed as guided-missile frigates (hull classification symbol DLG or DLGN, literally meaning guided-missile destroyer leaders), which were actually anti-aircraft warfare cruisers built on destroyer-style hulls.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These had one or two twin launchers per ship for the RIM-2 Terrier missile, upgraded to the RIM-67 Standard ER missile in the 1980s.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This type of ship was intended primarily to defend aircraft carriers against anti-ship cruise missiles, augmenting and eventually replacing converted World War II cruisers (CAG/CLG/CG) in this role.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The guided-missile frigates also had an anti-submarine capability that most of the World War II cruiser conversions lacked.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Some of these ships – *Bainbridge* and *Truxtun* along with the *California* and *Virginia* classes – were nuclear-powered (DLGN).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These "frigates" were roughly mid-way in size between cruisers and destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This was similar to the use of the term "frigate" during the age of sail during which it referred to a medium-sized warship, but it was inconsistent with conventions used by other contemporary navies which regarded frigates as being smaller than destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the late 1970s, as a gradual successor to the *Knox* frigates, the US Navy introduced the 51-ship *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class guided-missile frigates (FFG), the last of which was decommissioned in 2015, although some serve in other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] By 1995 the older guided-missile cruisers and destroyers were replaced by the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers and *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] One of the most successful post-1945 designs was the British *Leander*-class frigate, which was used by several navies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Laid down in 1959, the *Leander* class was based on the previous Type 12 anti-submarine frigate but equipped for anti-aircraft use as well.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] They were used by the UK into the 1990s, at which point some were sold on to other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The *Leander* design, or improved versions of it, were licence-built for other navies as well.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Nearly all modern frigates are equipped with some form of offensive or defensive missiles, and as such are rated as guided-missile frigates (FFG).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Improvements in surface-to-air missiles (e.g., the Eurosam Aster 15) allow modern guided-missile frigates to form the core of many modern navies and to be used as a fleet defence platform, without the need for specialised anti-air warfare frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] They can thus provide theatre wide air and missile defence for forces such as a carrier battle group and typically serve this function".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] By contrast the smaller "frigates are thus usually used as escort vessels to protect sea lines of communication or as an auxiliary component of a strike group".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The largest and most powerful destroyers, such as the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers, are often classified as cruisers due to their extra armament and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy Type 61 (*Salisbury* class) were "air direction" frigates equipped to track aircraft.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] To this end they had less armament than the Type 41 (*Leopard*-class) air-defence frigates built on the same hull.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Multi-role frigates such as the MEKO 200, *Anzac* and *Halifax* classes are designed for navies needing warships deployed in a variety of situations that a general frigate class would not be able to fulfil, and not requiring destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] At the opposite end of the spectrum, some frigates are specialised for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Increasing submarine speeds towards the end of World War II (see German Type XXI submarine) greatly reduced the margin of speed superiority of frigate over submarine.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate could no longer be slow and powered by mercantile machinery, and consequently postwar frigates such as the *Whitby* class were faster.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Such ships carry improved sonar equipment, such as the variable depth sonar or towed array, and specialised weapons such as torpedoes, forward-throwing weapons such as Limbo and missile-carried anti-submarine torpedoes such as ASROC or Ikara.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy's original Type 22 frigate is an example of a specialised anti-submarine warfare frigate, though it also has Sea Wolf surface-to-air missiles for point defence plus Exocet surface-to-surface missiles for limited offensive capability.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Especially for anti-submarine warfare, most modern frigates have a landing deck and hangar aft to operate helicopters, eliminating the need for the frigate to close with unknown sub-surface threats, and using fast helicopters to attack nuclear submarines which may be faster than surface warships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] For this task the helicopter is equipped with sensors such as sonobuoys, wire-mounted dipping sonar and magnetic anomaly detectors to identify possible threats, and torpedoes or depth-charges to attack them.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] With their onboard radar helicopters can also be used to reconnoitre over-the-horizon targets and, if equipped with anti-ship missiles such as Penguin or Sea Skua, to attack them.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The helicopter is also invaluable for search and rescue operation and has largely replaced the use of small boats or the jackstay rig for such duties as transferring personnel, mail and cargo between ships or to shore.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] With helicopters these tasks can be accomplished faster and less dangerously, and without the need for the frigate to slow down or change course.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates designed in the 1960s and 1970s, such as the US Navy's *Knox*-class frigate, West Germany's *Bremen*-class frigate, and Royal Navy's Type 22 frigate were equipped with a small number of short-ranged surface-to-air missiles (Sea Sparrow or Sea Wolf) for point defence only.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] By contrast newer frigates starting with the *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigate are specialised for "zone-defence" air defence, because of major developments in fighter jets and cruise missiles.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Recent examples include the *De Zeven Provinciën*-class air defence and command frigate of the Royal Netherlands Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Another example is the *Iver Huitfeldt* class of the Royal Danish Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Some new classes of ships similar to corvettes are optimized for high-speed deployment and combat with small craft rather than combat between equal opponents; an example is the U.S. littoral combat ship (LCS).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] As of 2015, all *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigates in the United States Navy have been decommissioned, and their role partially assumed by the new LCS.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] While the LCS class ships are smaller than the frigate class they will replace, they offer a similar degree of weaponry while requiring less than half the crew complement and offering a top speed of over 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] A major advantage for the LCS ships is that they are designed around specific mission modules allowing them to fulfil a variety of roles.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The modular system also allows for most upgrades to be performed ashore and installed later into the ship, keeping the ships available for deployment for the maximum time.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The latest U.S. deactivation plans make this the first time that the U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy has been without a frigate class of ships since 1943 (technically USS *Constitution* is rated as a frigate and is still in commission, but does not count towards Navy force levels).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The remaining 20 LCSs to be acquired from 2019 and onwards that will be enhanced will be designated as frigates, and existing ships given modifications may also have their classification changed to *FF* as well.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] However, the United States Navy selected a FREMM multipurpose frigate variant for a new *Constellation* class of 20 frigates, to be built by Fincantieri beginning in 2024.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Stealth technology has been introduced in modern frigate design by the French *La Fayette* class design.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigate shapes are designed to offer a minimal radar cross section, which also lends them good air penetration; the manoeuvrability of these frigates has been compared to that of sailing ships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The modern French Navy applies the term first-class frigate and second-class frigate to both destroyers and frigates in service.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Pennant numbers remain divided between F-series numbers for those ships internationally recognised as frigates and D-series pennant numbers for those more traditionally recognised as destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This can result in some confusion as certain classes are referred to as frigates in French service while similar ships in other navies are referred to as destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] This also results in some recent classes of French ships such as the Horizon class being among the largest in the world to carry the rating of frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The *Frégates de Taille Intermédiaire* (FTI), which means frigates of intermediate size, is a French military program to design and create a planned class of frigates to be used by the French Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] At the moment, the program consists of five ships, with commissioning planned from 2023.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] In the German Navy, frigates were used to replace ageing destroyers; however in size and role the new German frigates exceed the former class of destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The current German F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates are the largest class of frigates worldwide with a displacement of more than 7,200 tons .
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The same was done in the Spanish Navy, which went ahead with the deployment of the first Aegis frigates, the *Álvaro de Bazán*-class frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The Myanmar Navy is producing modern frigates with a reduced radar cross section known as the Kyan Sittha-class frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Before the Kyan Sittha class, the Myanmar Navy also produced an *Aung Zeya*-class frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] Although the size of the Myanmar Navy is quite small, it is producing modern guided-missile frigates with the help of Russia, China, and India.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] However, the fleets of the Myanmar Navy are still expanding with several on-going shipbuilding programmes, including one 135 m (442 ft 11 in), 4,000-tonne frigate with the vertical missile launch systems.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] The four planned *Tamandaré*-class frigates of the Brazilian Navy will be responsible for introducing ships with stealth technology in the national navy and the Latin American region, with the first boat expected to be launched in 2024.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] A few frigates have survived as museum ships.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/armoured-frigate-p01] These ships are classified by their respective nations as frigates, but are considered destroyers internationally due to size, armament, and role.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg had been a stronghold since Roman times, and was one of the strongest fortresses of the Hundred Years War.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] But until the 18th century it had only a shallow harbour, minor commercial activity and no military development.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] In the 17th century the military engineer Vauban drew up plans to develop Cherbourg into a port where passing ships could shelter from attack or storms.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Vauban's plans included an artificial harbour, and the quadrupling of the size of the city.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The project was eventually abandoned, before being temporarily revived under Louis XV.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The British raid on Cherbourg in 1758 however caused severe damage to the barely completed commercial port.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] By the 1770s, with French involvement in the American War of Independence, Louis XVI sought to create a large military port on the Cotentin Peninsula, allowing access into the English Channel, and comparable to that of Brest on the Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Two projects were drawn up and presented to the king in 1777.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The first, by the chief engineer of the bridges, roads and ports of the Caen region, Armand Lefebvre, called for the fortification of the Cherbourg roadstead around the enlarged commercial port.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The second project, by director of maritime engineering Antoine Choquet de Lindu, proposed the construction of a first class arsenal at La Hougue.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Naval officer Louis de La Couldre de La Bretonnière conducted a review of the proposals, which favoured the Cherbourg option.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] La Bretonnière recommended the construction of a jetty "two thousand toises long" between the tip of Querqueville and the reefs of Île Pelée, with the dredging of a harbour to a depth of 20 meters.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] La Bretonnière suggested the construction of a breakwater composed of sunken hulks and rocks, to be a foundation for further construction.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Ultimately an alternative proposal, by engineer Louis-Alexandre de Cessart, was preferred, that of a breakwater created by the sinking of 90 wooden cones weighted with stones, 50 meters in diameter at the base and 20 meters in height.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Work began in the 1780s. Île Pelée was fortified, and the wooden cones filled with stone were sunk outside the harbour(one in the presence of the king), to serve as a foundation for the breakwater.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The cones were damaged by bad weather, and were gradually replaced by a continuous breakwater in pierres perdues, when the works were interrupted by the French Revolution.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Work resumed in 1803 under the orders of First Consul Napoleon Bonaparte (decree of 25 Germinal year XI), as part of the plans to invade the United Kingdom.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] From 1803, protected from British attacks, Cherbourg became a haven for privateers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The breakwater was discontinued after 1813, to be resumed in 1830 and completed in 1853.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The engineer Joseph Cachin continued building the military port to the west of the town, the avant-port of which was opened on 27 August 1813 by Empress Marie-Louise.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] It was decided to establish the Arsenal in the same place.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Work began on the Charles X basin (420 × 200 × 18 meters) in 1814, and it was inaugurated on 25 August 1829 in the presence of the Dauphin.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] A second basin, Napoleon III (290 × 220 × 18 meters), was begun in 1836 and inaugurated on 7 August 1858 in the presence of Napoleon III and Empress Eugénie.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The continuous expansion of the military port and dockyard eventually came to consume between 3 and 4 million gold francs a year.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] By the end of the nineteenth century the United Kingdom was no longer the main adversary.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The city had become a major industrial centre and employer, with 4,000 workers from all over France based at the arsenal, which became the "backbone of the city".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] With the naval importance of the port reduced, the well-developed harbour became a base for transatlantic trade connecting northern Europe with the east coast of the Americas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The city was first bombed by the *Luftwaffe* on 15 June 1940, during the Battle of France.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The port was used as the evacuation point as British and French soldiers withdrew ahead of the advancing German Army, Cherbourg becoming the "Norman Dunkirk".
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The east fort on the breakwater was destroyed by the French Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] German forces arrived at Cherbourg on 17 June, and on 18 June the city council declared Cherbourg an open city.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Maritime prefect Vice-Admiral Jules Le Bigot ensured three submarines under construction at the arsenal, *Praya*, *Roland Morillot* and *Martinique*, were destroyed, and then surrendered the city to General Erwin Rommel.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg, the only deep-water port in the region, was the primary goal of US troops landed at Utah Beach during the allied invasion of Normandy.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg was vital in order to provide the Allies logistical support for the reinforcement and supply of the troops.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] US troops encircled the city on 21 June 1944.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Furious street fighting took place, with heavy supporting fire from allied warships against the German batteries.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] After strong resistance from Fort du Roule, General Karl-Wilhelm von Schlieben, Admiral Walter Hennecke and 37,000 soldiers surrendered on 26 June at 16:00 to General J.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The arsenal and the forts on the breakwater resisted for another day before they too surrendered.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The Germans had systematically damaged the port prior to surrendering.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Ships, tugs, cranes and other equipment had been thrown into the water in the basins, blocking the harbour and delaying the arrival of the first ships until the end of July.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] In November 1944, the local Cherbourg bailout commission was created to organise the salvaging of ships and clearing accesses to the port.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The port was only partially back in service by mid-August.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] On 14 July 1944 the Place du Château, renamed Place du Maréchal-Pétain during the German occupation, was renamed Place Général De Gaulle, while the Quai de l'Ancien-Arsenal was renamed Lawton-Collins Quay, after the American commander of VII Corps, which had liberated the city.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] American troops of the Fourth Major Port of Embarkation and French transport corps carried out sufficient repairs to the port for it to accommodate the first liberty ships a month after its capture.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] From then until the liberation of the port of Antwerp in November 1944, the daily landing of supplies and military equipment made Cherbourg the largest port in the world, twice that of the port of New York.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Fuel arrived in Cherbourg along the PLUTO pipeline, while men and the equipment were routed from the port to the front, travelling by road (the "Red Ball Express") and rail (the "Toot Sweet Express").
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] On 24 December 1944, the Belgian freighter SS *Léopoldville*, carrying 2,237 American soldiers of the 66th Infantry Division, was torpedoed by a German submarine off Cherbourg.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg was returned to France by the Americans on 14 October 1945.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] It is quoted in the order of the army of 2 June 1948 and was awarded the Croix de Guerre with palm.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg is one of three naval bases of metropolitan France (the other two are Brest and Toulon).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] With the departure of the Flotilla of the North (FLONOR), Cherbourg lost its importance as a port of registry.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The Channel Flotilla (Flomanche) monitors the English Channel and the North Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The arsenal of Cherbourg specializes in submarine construction.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] These are nuclear vessels for the French Navy, such as the *Triomphant* class and the planned *Suffren* class, or conventional diesel-electric propulsion vessels for export, such as the Scorpène type.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Faced with declining needs, the Navy has since 2000 opened the arsenal to the private sector.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/arsenal-de-cherbourg] It leases 50,000 m2 (540,000 sq ft) of land to two companies in its northern part: the Euriware secure management centre (100 employees) and the Ican shipyard (170 employees), specializing in the construction of service boats.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The **Atlantic Ocean** is the second largest of the world's five oceanic divisions, with an area of about 85,133,000 square kilometers (32,870,000 sq mi).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] It covers approximately 17% of Earth's surface and about 24% of its water surface area.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Age of Discovery, it was known for separating the New World of the Americas (North America and South America) from the Old World of Afro-Eurasia (Africa, Asia, and Europe).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Through its separation of Afro-Eurasia from the Americas, the Atlantic Ocean has played a central role in the development of human society, globalization, and the histories of many nations.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] While the Norse were the first known humans to cross the Atlantic, it was the expedition of Christopher Columbus in 1492 that proved to be the most consequential.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Columbus's expedition ushered in an age of exploration and colonization of the Americas by European powers, most notably Portugal, Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] From the 16th to 19th centuries, the Atlantic Ocean was the center of both an eponymous slave trade and the Columbian exchange while occasionally hosting naval battles.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Such naval battles, as well as growing trade from regional American powers like the United States and Brazil, both increased in degree during the early 20th century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] After World War II, major military operations became rarer, though notable postwar conflicts include the Cuban Missile Crisis and the Falklands War.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The ocean remains a core component of trade around the world.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean's temperatures vary by location.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] For example, the South Atlantic maintains warm temperatures year-round, as its basin countries are tropical.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The North Atlantic maintains a temperate climate, as its basin countries are temperate and have seasons of extremely low temperatures and high temperatures.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean occupies an elongated, S-shaped basin extending longitudinally between Europe and Africa to the east, and the Americas to the west.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] As one component of the interconnected World Ocean, it is connected in the north to the Arctic Ocean, to the Pacific Ocean in the southwest, the Indian Ocean in the southeast, and the Southern Ocean in the south.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other definitions describe the Atlantic as extending southward to Antarctica.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is divided in two parts, the northern and southern Atlantic, by the Equator.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oldest known mentions of an "Atlantic" sea come from Stesichorus around mid-sixth century BC (Sch.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] 211): *Atlantikôi pelágei* (Ancient Greek: Ἀτλαντικῷ πελάγει, 'the Atlantic sea', etym.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] 'Sea of Atlas') and in *The Histories* of Herodotus around 450 BC (Hdt.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] 1.202.4): *Atlantis thalassa* (Ancient Greek: Ἀτλαντὶς θάλασσα, 'Sea of Atlas' or 'the Atlantic sea'), where the name refers to "the sea beyond the pillars of Hercules" (the Strait of Gibraltar), beyond the Atlas Mountains in Morocco and off the West African coast.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In these uses, the name refers to Atlas, the Titan in Greek mythology, who supported the heavens and who later appeared as a frontispiece in medieval maps and atlases.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Early Greek sailors believed the Atlantic to be part of the Oceanus, the great sea or river that surrounds all land, mentioned in ancient Greek mythological literature such as the *Iliad* and *Odyssey*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This was in contrast to the enclosed seas well known to the Greeks, the Mediterranean and the Black Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The great ocean was believed to stretch around Africa, leading to the term "**Aethiopian Ocean**", derived from Ancient Ethiopia, applied to the southern Atlantic as late as the mid-19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Age of Discovery, the Atlantic was also known to English cartographers as the **Great Western Ocean**.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The International Hydrographic Organization (IHO) defined the limits of the oceans and seas in 1953, but some of these definitions have been revised since then and some are not recognized by various authorities, institutions, and countries, such as the CIA World Factbook, for example.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Correspondingly, the extent and number of oceans and seas vary.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is bounded on the west by North and South America.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] It connects to the Arctic Ocean through the Labrador Sea, Denmark Strait, Greenland Sea, Norwegian Sea and Barents Sea with the northern divider passing through Iceland and Svalbard.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] To the east, the boundaries of the ocean proper are Europe and Africa: the Strait of Gibraltar (where it connects with the Mediterranean Sea – one of its marginal seas – and, in turn, the Black Sea, both of which also touch upon Asia).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the southeast, the Atlantic merges into the Indian Ocean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The 20° East meridian, running south from Cape Agulhas to Antarctica defines its border.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the 1953 definition it extends south to Antarctica, while in later maps it is bounded at the 60° parallel by the Southern Ocean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic has irregular coasts indented by numerous bays, gulfs and seas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] These include the Baltic Sea, Black Sea, Caribbean Sea, Davis Strait, Denmark Strait, part of the Drake Passage, Gulf of Mexico, Labrador Sea, Mediterranean Sea, North Sea, Norwegian Sea, almost all of the Scotia Sea, and other tributary water bodies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Including these marginal seas the coast line of the Atlantic measures 111,866 km (69,510 mi) compared to 135,663 km (84,297 mi) for the Pacific.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Including its marginal seas, the Atlantic covers an area of 106,460,000 km2 (41,100,000 sq mi) or 23.5% of the global ocean and has a volume of 310,410,900 km3 (74,471,500 cu mi) or 23.3% of the total volume of the Earth's oceans.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The average depth is 3,646 m (11,962 ft) and the maximum depth, the Milwaukee Deep in the Puerto Rico Trench, is 8,376 m (27,480 ft).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The bathymetry of the Atlantic is dominated by a submarine mountain range called the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (MAR).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] It runs from 87°N or 300 km (190 mi) south of the North Pole to the subantarctic Bouvet Island at 54°S.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Expeditions to explore the bathymertry of the Atlantic include the *Challenger* expedition and the German *Meteor* expedition; as of 2001, Columbia University's Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory and the United States Navy Hydrographic Office conduct research on the ocean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR divides the Atlantic longitudinally into two halves, in each of which a series of basins are delimited by secondary, transverse ridges.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR reaches above 2,000 m (6,600 ft) along most of its length, but is interrupted by larger transform faults at two places: the Romanche Trench near the Equator and the Gibbs fracture zone at 53°N.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR is a barrier for bottom water, but at these two transform faults deep water currents can pass from one side to the other.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR rises 2–3 km (1.2–1.9 mi) above the surrounding ocean floor and its rift valley is the divergent boundary between the North American and Eurasian plates in the North Atlantic and the South American and African plates in the South Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR produces basaltic volcanoes in Eyjafjallajökull, Iceland, and pillow lava on the ocean floor.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The depth of water at the apex of the ridge is less than 2,700 m (1,500 fathoms; 8,900 ft) in most places, while the bottom of the ridge is three times as deep.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR is intersected by two perpendicular ridges: the Azores–Gibraltar transform fault, the boundary between the Nubian and Eurasian plates, intersects the MAR at the Azores triple junction, on either side of the Azores microplate, near the 40°N.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] A much vaguer, nameless boundary, between the North American and South American plates, intersects the MAR near or just north of the Fifteen-Twenty fracture zone, approximately at 16°N.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The remainder of the ridge was discovered in the 1920s by the German *Meteor* expedition using echo-sounding equipment.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The exploration of the MAR in the 1950s led to the general acceptance of seafloor spreading and plate tectonics.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Most of the MAR runs under water but where it reaches the surfaces it has produced volcanic islands.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Continental shelves in the Atlantic are wide off Newfoundland, southernmost South America, and northeastern Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the western Atlantic carbonate platforms dominate large areas, for example, the Blake Plateau and Bermuda Rise.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic is surrounded by passive margins except at a few locations where active margins form deep trenches: the Puerto Rico Trench (8,376 m or 27,480 ft maximum depth) in the western Atlantic and South Sandwich Trench (8,264 m or 27,113 ft) in the South Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] There are numerous submarine canyons off northeastern North America, western Europe, and northwestern Africa.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Some of these canyons extend along the continental rises and farther into the abyssal plains as deep-sea channels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1922, a historic moment in cartography and oceanography occurred.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The USS *Stewart* used a Navy Sonic Depth Finder to draw a continuous map across the bed of the Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This involved little guesswork because the idea of sonar is straightforward with pulses being sent from the vessel, which bounce off the ocean floor, then return to the vessel.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The deep ocean floor is thought to be fairly flat with occasional deeps, abyssal plains, trenches, seamounts, basins, plateaus, canyons, and some guyots.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Various shelves along the margins of the continents constitute about 11% of the bottom topography with few deep channels cut across the continental rise.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The mean depth between 60°N and 60°S is 3,730 m (12,240 ft), or close to the average for the global ocean, with a modal depth between 4,000 and 5,000 m (13,000 and 16,000 ft).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the South Atlantic the Walvis Ridge and Rio Grande Rise form barriers to ocean currents.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Laurentian Abyss is found off the eastern coast of Canada.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Surface water temperatures, which vary with latitude, current systems, and season and reflect the latitudinal distribution of solar energy, range from below −2 °C (28 °F) to over 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Maximum temperatures occur north of the equator, and minimum values are found in the polar regions.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the middle latitudes, the area of maximum temperature variations, values may vary by 7–8 °C (13–14 °F).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] From October to June the surface is usually covered with sea ice in the Labrador Sea, Denmark Strait, and Baltic Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Coriolis effect circulates North Atlantic water in a clockwise direction, whereas South Atlantic water circulates counter-clockwise.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The south tides in the Atlantic Ocean are semi-diurnal; that is, two high tides occur every 24 lunar hours.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In latitudes above 40° North some east–west oscillation, known as the North Atlantic oscillation, occurs.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] On average, the Atlantic is the saltiest major ocean; surface water salinity in the open ocean ranges from 33 to 37 parts per thousand (3.3–3.7%) by mass and varies with latitude and season.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Evaporation, precipitation, river inflow and sea ice melting influence surface salinity values.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Although the lowest salinity values are just north of the equator (because of heavy tropical rainfall), in general, the lowest values are in the high latitudes and along coasts where large rivers enter.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Maximum salinity values occur at about 25° north and south, in subtropical regions with low rainfall and high evaporation.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The high surface salinity in the Atlantic, on which the Atlantic thermohaline circulation is dependent, is maintained by two processes.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Agulhas Leakage/Rings brings salty Indian Ocean waters into the South Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] While the "Atmospheric Bridge" evaporates subtropical Atlantic waters and exports it to the Pacific.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean consists of four major, upper water masses with distinct temperature and salinity.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic subarctic upper water in the northernmost North Atlantic is the source for subarctic intermediate water and North Atlantic intermediate water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic central water can be divided into the eastern and western North Atlantic central water since the western part is strongly affected by the Gulf Stream and therefore the upper layer is closer to underlying fresher subpolar intermediate water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The eastern water is saltier because of its proximity to Mediterranean water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic central water flows into South Atlantic central water at 15°N.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] There are five intermediate waters: four low-salinity waters formed at subpolar latitudes and one high-salinity formed through evaporation.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Arctic intermediate water flows from the north to become the source for North Atlantic deep water, south of the Greenland-Scotland sill.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] These two intermediate waters have different salinity in the western and eastern basins.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The wide range of salinities in the North Atlantic is caused by the asymmetry of the northern subtropical gyre and a large number of contributions from a wide range of sources: Labrador Sea, Norwegian-Greenland Sea, Mediterranean, and South Atlantic Intermediate Water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Along its path across Earth the composition of the NADW is affected by other water masses, especially Antarctic bottom water and Mediterranean overflow water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The NADW is fed by a flow of warm shallow water into the northern North Atlantic which is responsible for the anomalous warm climate in Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Changes in the formation of NADW have been linked to global climate changes in the past.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Since human-made substances were introduced into the environment, the path of the NADW can be traced throughout its course by measuring tritium and radiocarbon from nuclear weapon tests in the 1960s and CFCs.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The clockwise warm-water North Atlantic Gyre occupies the northern Atlantic, and the counter-clockwise warm-water South Atlantic Gyre appears in the southern Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This system of currents transports warm water into the North Atlantic, without which temperatures in the North Atlantic and Europe would plunge dramatically.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] North of the North Atlantic Gyre, the cyclonic North Atlantic Subpolar Gyre plays a key role in climate variability.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] It is governed by ocean currents from marginal seas and regional topography, rather than being steered by wind, both in the deep ocean and at sea level.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The subpolar gyre forms an important part of the global thermohaline circulation.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Its eastern portion includes eddying branches of the North Atlantic Current which transport warm, saline waters from the subtropics to the northeastern Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] There this water is cooled during winter and forms return currents that merge along the eastern continental slope of Greenland where they form an intense (40–50 Sv) current which flows around the continental margins of the Labrador Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] A third of this water becomes part of the deep portion of the North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The NADW, in turn, feeds the meridional overturning circulation (MOC), the northward heat transport of which is threatened by anthropogenic climate change.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Large variations in the subpolar gyre on a decade-century scale, associated with the North Atlantic oscillation, are especially pronounced in Labrador Sea Water, the upper layers of the MOC.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The South Atlantic is dominated by the anti-cyclonic southern subtropical gyre.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The South Atlantic Central Water originates in this gyre, while Antarctic Intermediate Water originates in the upper layers of the circumpolar region, near the Drake Passage and the Falkland Islands.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Both these currents receive some contribution from the Indian Ocean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] On the African east coast, the small cyclonic Angola Gyre lies embedded in the large subtropical gyre.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The southern subtropical gyre is partly masked by a wind-induced Ekman layer.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The residence time of the gyre is 4.4–8.5 years.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic Deep Water flows southward below the thermocline of the subtropical gyre.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Sargasso Sea in the western North Atlantic can be defined as the area where two species of *Sargassum* (*S. fluitans* and *natans*) float, an area 4,000 km (2,500 mi) wide and encircled by the Gulf Stream, North Atlantic Drift, and North Equatorial Current.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This population of seaweed probably originated from Tertiary ancestors on the European shores of the former Tethys Ocean and has, if so, maintained itself by vegetative growth, floating in the ocean for millions of years.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other species endemic to the Sargasso Sea include the sargassum fish, a predator with algae-like appendages which hovers motionless among the *Sargassum*.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Fossils of similar fishes have been found in fossil bays of the former Tethys Ocean, in what is now the Carpathian region, that were similar to the Sargasso Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] It is possible that the population in the Sargasso Sea migrated to the Atlantic as the Tethys closed at the end of the Miocene around 17 Ma.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The origin of the Sargasso fauna and flora remained enigmatic for centuries.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The fossils found in the Carpathians in the mid-20th century often called the "quasi-Sargasso assemblage", finally showed that this assemblage originated in the Carpathian Basin from where it migrated over Sicily to the central Atlantic where it evolved into modern species of the Sargasso Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The location of the spawning ground for European eels remained unknown for decades.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the early 19th century it was discovered that the southern Sargasso Sea is the spawning ground for both the European and American eel and that the former migrate more than 5,000 km (3,100 mi) and the latter 2,000 km (1,200 mi).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Ocean currents such as the Gulf Stream transport eel larvae from the Sargasso Sea to foraging areas in North America, Europe, and northern Africa.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Recent but disputed research suggests that eels possibly use Earth's magnetic field to navigate through the ocean both as larvae and as adults.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The climate is influenced by the temperatures of the surface waters and water currents as well as winds.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Because of the ocean's great capacity to store and release heat, maritime climates are more moderate and have less extreme seasonal variations than inland climates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Precipitation can be approximated from coastal weather data and air temperature from water temperatures.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oceans are the major source of atmospheric moisture that is obtained through evaporation.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Climatic zones vary with latitude; the warmest zones stretch across the Atlantic north of the equator.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The coldest zones are in high latitudes, with the coldest regions corresponding to the areas covered by sea ice.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Ocean currents influence the climate by transporting warm and cold waters to other regions.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The winds that are cooled or warmed when blowing over these currents influence adjacent land areas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gulf Stream and its northern extension towards Europe, the North Atlantic Drift is thought to have at least some influence on climate.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] For example, the Gulf Stream helps moderate winter temperatures along the coastline of southeastern North America, keeping it warmer in winter along the coast than inland areas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gulf Stream also keeps extreme temperatures from occurring on the Florida Peninsula.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the higher latitudes, the North Atlantic Drift, warms the atmosphere over the oceans, keeping the British Isles and northwestern Europe mild and cloudy, and not severely cold in winter, like other locations at the same high latitude.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The cold water currents contribute to heavy fog off the coast of eastern Canada (the Grand Banks of Newfoundland area) and Africa's northwestern coast.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In general, winds transport moisture and air over land areas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Every winter, the Icelandic Low produces frequent storms.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Icebergs are common from early February to the end of July across the shipping lanes near the Grand Banks of Newfoundland.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The ice season is longer in the polar regions, but there is little shipping in those areas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Hurricanes are a hazard in the western parts of the North Atlantic during the summer and autumn.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Due to a consistently strong wind shear and a weak Intertropical Convergence Zone, South Atlantic tropical cyclones are rare.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is underlain mostly by dense mafic oceanic crust made up of basalt and gabbro and overlain by fine clay, silt and siliceous ooze on the abyssal plain.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The continental margins and continental shelf mark lower density, but greater thickness felsic continental rock that is often much older than that of the seafloor.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oldest oceanic crust in the Atlantic is up to 145 million years and is situated off the west coast of Africa and the east coast of North America, or on either side of the South Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In many places, the continental shelf and continental slope are covered in thick sedimentary layers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] For instance, on the North American side of the ocean, large carbonate deposits formed in warm shallow waters such as Florida and the Bahamas, while coarse river outwash sands and silt are common in shallow shelf areas like the Georges Bank.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Coarse sand, boulders, and rocks were transported into some areas, such as off the coast of Nova Scotia or the Gulf of Maine during the Pleistocene ice ages.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The break-up of Pangaea began in the central Atlantic, between North America and Northwest Africa, where rift basins opened during the Late Triassic and Early Jurassic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This period also saw the first stages of the uplift of the Atlas Mountains.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The exact timing is controversial with estimates ranging from 200 to 170 Ma.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Theoliitic dikes, sills, and lava flows from the CAMP eruption at 200 Ma have been found in West Africa, eastern North America, and northern South America.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The extent of the volcanism has been estimated to 4.5×106 km2 (1.7×106 sq mi) of which 2.5×106 km2 (9.7×105 sq mi) covered what is now northern and central Brazil.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The formation of the Central American Isthmus closed the Central American Seaway at the end of the Pliocene 2.8 Ma ago.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The formation of the isthmus resulted in the migration and extinction of many land-living animals, known as the Great American Interchange, but the closure of the seaway resulted in a "Great American Schism" as it affected ocean currents, salinity, and temperatures in both the Atlantic and Pacific.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Marine organisms on both sides of the isthmus became isolated and either diverged or went extinct.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Geologically, the North Atlantic is the area delimited to the south by two conjugate margins, Newfoundland and Iberia, and to the north by the Arctic Eurasian Basin.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The opening of the North Atlantic closely followed the margins of its predecessor, the Iapetus Ocean, and spread from the central Atlantic in six stages: Iberia–Newfoundland, Porcupine–North America, Eurasia–Greenland, Eurasia–North America.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Active and inactive spreading systems in this area are marked by the interaction with the Iceland hotspot.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Seafloor spreading led to the extension of the crust and the formation of troughs and sedimentary basins.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Rockall Trough opened between 105 and 84 million years ago although the rift failed along with one leading into the Bay of Biscay.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Spreading began opening the Labrador Sea around 61 million years ago, continuing until 36 million years ago.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Geologists distinguish two magmatic phases.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] One from 62 to 58 million years ago predates the separation of Greenland from northern Europe while the second from 56 to 52 million years ago happened as the separation occurred.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Iceland began to form 62 million years ago due to a particularly concentrated mantle plume.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Large quantities of basalt erupted at this time period are found on Baffin Island, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, and Scotland, with ash falls in Western Europe acting as a stratigraphic marker.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The opening of the North Atlantic caused a significant uplift of continental crust along the coast.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] For instance, despite 7 km thick basalt, Gunnbjorn Field in East Greenland is the highest point on the island, elevated enough that it exposes older Mesozoic sedimentary rocks at its base, similar to old lava fields above sedimentary rocks in the uplifted Hebrides of western Scotland.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The North Atlantic Ocean contains about 810 seamounts, most of them situated along the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The OSPAR database (Convention for the Protection of the Marine Environment of the North-East Atlantic) mentions 104 seamounts: 74 within national exclusive economic zones.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Of these seamounts, 46 are located close to the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] West Gondwana (South America and Africa) broke up in the Early Cretaceous to form the South Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The apparent fit between the coastlines of the two continents was noted on the first maps that included the South Atlantic and it was also the subject of the first computer-assisted plate tectonic reconstructions in 1965.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This magnificent fit, however, has since then proven problematic and later reconstructions have introduced various deformation zones along the shorelines to accommodate the northward-propagating break-up.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Intra-continental rifts and deformations have also been introduced to subdivide both continental plates into sub-plates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the southern segment the Early Cretaceous (133–130 Ma) intensive magmatism of the Paraná–Etendeka Large Igneous Province produced by the Tristan hotspot resulted in an estimated volume of 1.5×106 to 2.0×106 km3 (3.6×105 to 4.8×105 cu mi).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Dyke swarms in Brazil, Angola, eastern Paraguay, and Namibia, however, suggest the LIP originally covered a much larger area and also indicate failed rifts in all these areas.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Associated offshore basaltic flows reach as far south as the Falkland Islands and South Africa.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Traces of magmatism in both offshore and onshore basins in the central and southern segments have been dated to 147–49 Ma with two peaks between 143 and 121 Ma and 90–60 Ma.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the Falkland segment rifting began with dextral movements between the Patagonia and Colorado sub-plates between the Early Jurassic (190 Ma) and the Early Cretaceous (126.7 Ma).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Around 150 Ma sea-floor spreading propagated northward into the southern segment.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] No later than 130 Ma rifting had reached the Walvis Ridge–Rio Grande Rise.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the central segment, rifting started to break Africa in two by opening the Benue Trough around 118 Ma.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Rifting in the central segment, however, coincided with the Cretaceous Normal Superchron (also known as the Cretaceous quiet period), a 40 Ma period without magnetic reversals, which makes it difficult to date sea-floor spreading in this segment.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The equatorial segment is the last phase of the break-up, but, because it is located on the Equator, magnetic anomalies cannot be used for dating.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Various estimates date the propagation of seafloor spreading in this segment and consequent opening of the Equatorial Atlantic Gateway (EAG) to the period 120–96 Ma.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This final stage, nevertheless, coincided with or resulted in the end of continental extension in Africa.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] About 50 Ma the opening of the Drake Passage resulted from a change in the motions and separation rate of the South American and Antarctic plates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] First, small ocean basins opened and a shallow gateway appeared during the Middle Eocene.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] 34–30 Ma a deeper seaway developed, followed by an Eocene–Oligocene climatic deterioration and the growth of the Antarctic ice sheet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] An embryonic subduction margin is potentially developing west of Gibraltar.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gibraltar Arc in the western Mediterranean is migrating westward into the central Atlantic where it joins the converging African and Eurasian plates.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Together these three tectonic forces are slowly developing into a new subduction system in the eastern Atlantic Basin.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Meanwhile, the Scotia Arc and Caribbean plate in the western Atlantic Basin are eastward-propagating subduction systems that might, together with the Gibraltar system, represent the beginning of the closure of the Atlantic Ocean and the final stage of the Atlantic Wilson cycle.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other theories propose that the Atlantic will continue to widen while the Pacific Ocean closes first.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This would create the future supercontinent Amasia.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This theory states over the next 200 to 300 million years, dominant subduction in the Pacific will close the ocean while the Atlantic continues to get wider.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) studies indicate that 80,000–60,000 years ago a major demographic expansion within Africa, derived from a single, small population, coincided with the emergence of behavioral complexity and the rapid MIS 5–4 environmental changes.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This group of people not only expanded over the whole of Africa, but also started to disperse out of Africa into Asia, Europe, and Australasia around 65,000 years ago and quickly replaced the archaic humans in these regions.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) 20,000 years ago humans had to abandon their initial settlements along the European North Atlantic coast and retreat to the Mediterranean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Following rapid climate changes at the end of the LGM this region was repopulated by Magdalenian culture.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other hunter-gatherers followed in waves interrupted by hazards such as the Laacher See volcanic eruption, the inundation of Doggerland (now the North Sea), and the formation of the Baltic Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The European coasts of the North Atlantic were permanently populated about 9,000–8.5,000 years ago.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This human dispersal left abundant traces along the coasts of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] 50 kya-old, deeply stratified shell middens found in Ysterfontein on the western coast of South Africa are associated with the Middle Stone Age (MSA).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MSA population was small and dispersed and the rate of their reproduction and exploitation was less intense than those of later generations.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] While their middens resemble 12–11 kya-old Late Stone Age (LSA) middens found on every inhabited continent, the 50–45 kya-old Enkapune Ya Muto in Kenya probably represents the oldest traces of the first modern humans to disperse out of Africa.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The same development can be seen in Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In La Riera Cave (23–13 kya) in Asturias, Spain, only some 26,600 molluscs were deposited over 10 kya.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In contrast, 8–7 kya-old shell middens in Portugal, Denmark, and Brazil generated thousands of tons of debris and artefacts.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Ertebølle middens in Denmark, for example, accumulated 2,000 m3 (71,000 cu ft) of shell deposits representing some 50 million molluscs over only a thousand years.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The earliest exploitation took place on the submerged shelves, now submerged and most settlements now excavated were then located several kilometers from these shelves.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The reduced quantities of shells in the lower levels can represent the few shells that were exported inland.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the LGM the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered most of northern North America while Beringia connected Siberia to Alaska.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1973, late American geoscientist Paul S.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Furthermore, colonisation models based on mtDNA, yDNA, and atDNA data respectively support neither the "blitzkrieg" nor the "three-wave" hypotheses but they also deliver mutually ambiguous results.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Contradictory data from archaeology and genetics will most likely deliver future hypotheses that will, eventually, confirm each other.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] A proposed route across the Pacific to South America could explain early South American finds and another hypothesis proposes a northern path, through the Canadian Arctic and down the North American Atlantic coast.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Early settlements across the Atlantic have been suggested by alternative theories, ranging from purely hypothetical to mostly disputed, including the Solutrean hypothesis and some of the Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact theories.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Norse settlement of the Faroe Islands and Iceland began during the 9th and 10th centuries.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] A settlement on Greenland was established before 1000 CE, but contact with it was lost in 1409 and it was finally abandoned during the early Little Ice Age.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Iceland was initially settled 865–930 CE following a warm period when winter temperatures hovered around 2 °C (36 °F) which made farming favorable at high latitudes.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] This did not last, however, and temperatures quickly dropped; at 1080 CE summer temperatures had reached a maximum of 5 °C (41 °F).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The *Landnámabók* (*Book of Settlement*) records disastrous famines during the first century of settlement – "men ate foxes and ravens" and "the old and helpless were killed and thrown over cliffs" – and by the early 1200s hay had to be abandoned for short-season crops such as barley.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492, sailing under the Spanish flag.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Six years later Vasco da Gama reached India under the Portuguese flag, by navigating south around the Cape of Good Hope, thus proving that the Atlantic and Indian Oceans are connected.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1500, in his voyage to India following Vasco da Gama, Pedro Álvares Cabral reached Brazil, taken by the currents of the South Atlantic Gyre.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Following these explorations, Spain and Portugal quickly conquered and colonized large territories in the New World and forced the Amerindian population into slavery in order to exploit the vast quantities of silver and gold they found.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Spain and Portugal monopolized this trade in order to keep other European nations out, but conflicting interests nevertheless led to a series of Spanish-Portuguese wars.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] A peace treaty mediated by the Pope divided the conquered territories into Spanish and Portuguese sectors while keeping other colonial powers away.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] England, France, and the Dutch Republic enviously watched the Spanish and Portuguese wealth grow and allied themselves with pirates such as Henry Mainwaring and Alexandre Exquemelin.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] They could explore the convoys leaving the Americas because prevailing winds and currents made the transport of heavy metals slow and predictable.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Between the 15th century and 1888, when Brazil became the last part of the Americas to end the slave trade, an estimated 9.5 million enslaved Africans were shipped into the New World, most of them destined for agricultural labor.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] The slave trade was officially abolished in the British Empire and the United States in 1808, and slavery itself was abolished in the British Empire in 1838 and in the United States in 1865 after the Civil War.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] From Columbus to the Industrial Revolution trans-Atlantic trade, including colonialism and slavery, became crucial for Western Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] For European countries with direct access to the Atlantic (including Britain, France, the Netherlands, Portugal, and Spain) 1500–1800 was a period of sustained growth during which these countries grew richer than those in Eastern Europe and Asia.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Colonialism evolved as part of the trans-Atlantic trade, but this trade also strengthened the position of merchant groups at the expense of monarchs.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Growth was more rapid in non-absolutist countries, such as Britain and the Netherlands, and more limited in absolutist monarchies, such as Portugal, Spain, and France, where profit mostly or exclusively benefited the monarchy and its allies.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Trans-Atlantic trade also resulted in increasing urbanization: in European countries facing the Atlantic, urbanization grew from 8% in 1300, 10.1% in 1500, to 24.5% in 1850; in other European countries from 10% in 1300, 11.4% in 1500, to 17% in 1850.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] Likewise, GDP doubled in Atlantic countries but rose by only 30% in the rest of Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p01] By the end of the 17th century, the volume of the Trans-Atlantic trade had surpassed that of the Mediterranean trade.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The Atlantic has contributed significantly to the development and economy of surrounding countries.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Besides major transatlantic transportation and communication routes, the Atlantic offers abundant petroleum deposits in the sedimentary rocks of the continental shelves.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The Atlantic harbors petroleum and gas fields, fish, marine mammals (seals and whales), sand and gravel aggregates, placer deposits, polymetallic nodules, and precious stones.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Gold deposits are a mile or two underwater on the ocean floor, however, the deposits are also encased in rock that must be mined through.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Currently, there is no cost-effective way to mine or extract gold from the ocean to make a profit.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Various international treaties attempt to reduce pollution caused by environmental threats such as oil spills, marine debris, and the incineration of toxic wastes at sea.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The shelves of the Atlantic hosts one of the world's richest fishing resources.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The most productive areas include the Grand Banks of Newfoundland, the Scotian Shelf, Georges Bank off Cape Cod, the Bahama Banks, the waters around Iceland, the Irish Sea, the Bay of Fundy, the Dogger Bank of the North Sea, and the Falkland Banks.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The third group, "continuously increasing trend since 1950", is only found in the Indian Ocean and western Pacific.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Northeast Atlantic is schematically limited to the 40°00' west longitude (except around Greenland), south to the 36°00' north latitude, and to the 68°30' east longitude, with both the west and east longitude limits reaching to the north pole.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northeast Atlantic total catches decreased between the mid-1970s and the 1990s and reached 8.7 million tons in 2013.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] reached a 2.4 million tons peak in 2004 but was down to 628,000 tons in 2013.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Recovery plans for cod, sole, and plaice have reduced mortality in these species.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] reached its lowest levels in the 1960s–1980s but is now recovered.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] which has now recovered to fully fished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] and deep-water species difficult to assess but most likely they remain vulnerable to overfishing.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northeast Atlantic, 21% of stocks are considered overfished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Main fishing EU countries are Denmark, France, the Netherlands and Spain.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northwest Atlantic landings have decreased from 4.2 million tons in the early 1970s to 1.9 million tons in 2013.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Stocks of invertebrates, in contrast, remain at record levels of abundance.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] 31% of stocks are overfished in the northwest Atlantic.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In 1497, John Cabot became the first Western European since the Vikings to explore mainland North America and one of his major discoveries was the abundant resources of Atlantic cod off Newfoundland.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Referred to as "Newfoundland Currency" this discovery yielded some 200 million tons of fish over five centuries.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, new fisheries started to exploit haddock, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, the introduction of European and Asian distant-water fleets in the area dramatically increased the fishing capacity and the number of exploited species.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] It also expanded the exploited areas from near-shore to the open sea and to great depths to include deep-water species such as redfish, Greenland halibut, witch flounder, and grenadiers.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Overfishing in the area was recognized as early as the 1960s but, because this was occurring on international waters, it took until the late 1970s before any attempts to regulate was made.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the early 1990s, this finally resulted in the collapse of the Atlantic northwest cod fishery.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The population of a number of deep-sea fishes also collapsed in the process, including American plaice, redfish, and Greenland halibut, together with flounder and grenadier.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] constitute about 50% of landings with sardine reaching 0.6–1.0 million tons per year.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Almost half of the stocks are fished at biologically unsustainable levels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Total catches have been fluctuating since the 1970s; reaching 3.9 million tons in 2013 or slightly less than the peak production in 2010.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the western central-Atlantic, catches have been decreasing since 2000 and reached 1.3 million tons in 2013.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] , reached a million tons in the mid-1980s but only half a million tons in 2013 and is now considered fully fished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] was an important species in the 1990s but is now considered overfished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] are considered fully fished approaching overfished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] 44% of stocks are being fished at unsustainable levels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the southeast Atlantic catches have decreased from 3.3 million tons in the early 1970s to 1.3 million tons in 2013.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] are the most important species, together representing almost half of the landings.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the southwest Atlantic, a peak was reached in the mid-1980s and catches now fluctuate between 1.7 and 2.6 million tons.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] , which reached half a million tons in 2013 or half the peak value, is considered fully fished to overfished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] , with a production of 100,000 tons in 2013 it is now considered overfished.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Endangered marine species include the manatee, seals, sea lions, turtles, and whales.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Drift net fishing can kill dolphins, albatrosses and other seabirds (petrels, auks), hastening the fish stock decline and contributing to international disputes.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Marine pollution is a generic term for the entry into the ocean of potentially hazardous chemicals or particles.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The biggest culprits are rivers which carry many agricultural fertilizer chemicals as well as livestock and human waste.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The excess of oxygen-depleting chemicals leads to hypoxia and the creation of a dead zone.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Marine debris, which is also known as marine litter, describes human-created waste floating in a body of water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Oceanic debris tends to accumulate at the center of gyres and coastlines, frequently washing aground where it is known as beach litter.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The North Atlantic garbage patch is estimated to be hundreds of kilometers across in size.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Other pollution concerns include agricultural and municipal waste.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] A USAF C-124 aircraft from Dover Air Force Base, Delaware was carrying three nuclear bombs over the Atlantic Ocean when it experienced a loss of power.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] For their own safety, the crew jettisoned two nuclear bombs, which were never recovered.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] North Atlantic hurricane activity has increased over past decades because of increased sea surface temperature (SST) at tropical latitudes, changes that can be attributed to either the natural Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) or to anthropogenic climate change.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] A 2005 report indicated that the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC) slowed down by 30% between 1957 and 2004.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] In 2024, the research highlighted a significant weakening of the AMOC by approximately 12% over the past two decades.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] If the AMO were responsible for SST variability, the AMOC would have increased in strength, which is apparently not the case.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Furthermore, it is clear from statistical analyses of annual tropical cyclones that these changes do not display multidecadal cyclicity.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] Therefore, these changes in SST must be caused by human activities.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] The ocean mixed layer plays an important role in heat storage over seasonal and decadal time scales, whereas deeper layers are affected over millennia and have a heat capacity about 50 times that of the mixed layer.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/atlantic-ocean-p02] This heat uptake provides a time-lag for climate change but it also results in thermal expansion of the oceans which contributes to sea level rise.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/barquentine] A **barquentine** or **schooner barque** (alternatively "barkentine" or "schooner bark") is a sailing vessel with three or more masts, with a square rigged foremast and fore-and-aft rigged main, mizzen and any other masts.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/barquentine] While a full-rigged ship is square-rigged on all three masts, and the barque is square-rigged except for the mizzen-mast, the barquentine extends the principle by making only the foremast square-rigged.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/barquentine] The advantages of a smaller crew, good performance before the wind and the ability to sail relatively close to the wind while carrying plenty of cargo made it a popular rig at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/barquentine] Today, barquentines are popular with modern tall ship and sail training operators as their suite of mainly fore-and-aft sails improve non-downwind performance, while their foremast of square sails offers long distance downwind speed and dramatic appearance in port.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/barquentine] The term "barquentine" is seventeenth-century in origin, formed from "barque" in imitation of "brigantine", a two-masted vessel square-rigged only on the forward mast, and apparently formed from the word brig.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] The **beam** of a ship is its width at its widest point.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] The **maximum beam** (BMAX) is the distance between planes passing through the outer sides of the ship, **beam of the hull** (BH) only includes permanently fixed parts of the hull, and **beam at waterline** (BWL) is the maximum width where the hull intersects the surface of the water.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] Generally speaking, the wider the beam of a ship (or boat), the more initial stability it has, at the expense of secondary stability in the event of a capsize, where more energy is required to right the vessel from its inverted position.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] A ship that heels on her *beam ends* has her deck beams nearly vertical.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] Typical length-to-beam ratios (aspect ratios) for small sailboats are from 2:1 (dinghies to trailerable sailboats around 20 ft or 6 m) to 5:1 (racing sailboats over 30 ft or 10 m).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] Large ships have widely varying beam ratios, some as large as 20:1.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] Rowing shells designed for flatwater racing may have length to beam ratios as high as 30:1, while a coracle has a ratio of almost 1:1 – it is nearly circular.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] Where LOA is Length OverAll and all lengths are in feet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] As catamarans have more than one hull, there is a different beam calculation for this kind of vessel.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] This term in typically used in conjunction with LOA (Length overall).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] The ratio of LOA/BOC is used to estimate the stability of multihull vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] The lower the ratio the greater the boat's stability.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/beam-nautical] The BOC for vessels is measured as follows: For a catamaran: the perpendicular distance from the centerline of one hull to the centerline of the other hull, measured at deck level.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] A native of Bayonne, Jauréguiberry entered the French Navy in 1831.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] He became a lieutenant in 1845, a commander in 1856, and a captain in 1860.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] After serving in the Crimea and in China, and being governor of Senegal, he was promoted to rear admiral in 1869.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] Jauréguiberry served in the Crimean War as commander of the gunboat *Grenade*, distinguishing himself at the capture of Kinburn on 17 October 1855.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] He was twice commended for his conduct in orders of the day.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] He served on land during the second part of the Franco-Prussian War, in the rank of auxiliary general of division.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] He was present at the battles of Coulmiers, Villepion and Loigny-Poupry, in command of a division, and in Chanzy's retreat upon Le Mans and the battle at that place in command of a corps.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] Jauréguiberry had been amongst the most distinguished French naval officers in the military campaigns of the period.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] On 9 December he had been made vice admiral, and in 1871 he commanded the fleet at Toulon; in 1875 he was a member of the council of admiralty; and in October 1876 he was appointed to command the evolutionary squadron in the Mediterranean.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] In February 1879 he became minister of the navy in the Waddington cabinet, and on 27 May following was elected a senator for life.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] He was again minister of the navy in the Freycinet cabinet in 1880.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] He then served as the Minister of Marine and Colonies in the Charles Duclerc government from 1882 to 1883.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] A fine example of the fighting French seaman of his time, Jaureguiberry died at Paris in October 1887.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/bernard-jauréguiberry] Two French ships have been named in the admiral's honour, the pre-dreadnought battleship *Jauréguiberry*, in service from 1897 to 1919, and the fleet escort (T 53-class destroyer) *Jauréguiberry*, in service from 1958 to 1977.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The **French ironclad *Normandie*** was the third and last of the three wooden-hulled *Gloire*-class ironclads built for the French Navy in 1858–62.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The ships of the *Gloire* class were classified as armoured frigates because they only had a single gun deck and their traditional disposition of guns arrayed along the length of the hull also meant that they were broadside ironclads.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] *Normandie* was the first ironclad to cross the Atlantic in support of the French intervention in Mexico in 1862.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] Although the ship was active during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71, she saw no action.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The unseasoned timber of her hull rotted quickly; she was condemned in 1871 and subsequently scrapped.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] Designed by the French naval architect Henri Dupuy de Lôme, the ships of the class were intended to fight in the line of battle, unlike the first British ironclads.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The ship was 77.25 metres (253 ft 5 in) long, with a beam of 17 metres (55 ft 9 in).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] *Normandie* had a maximum draft of 8.48 metres (27 ft 10 in), a depth of hold of 10.67 metres (35 ft 0 in) and displaced 5,650 tonnes (5,560 long tons).
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The ships of the class had a high metacentric height of 2.1 metres (7 ft) and consequently rolled badly.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] With their gun ports only 1.88 metres (6 ft 2 in) above the waterline, they proved to be very wet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The *Gloire*-class ships were armed with 36 Modèle 1858 164.7-millimetre (6.5 in) broadside.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The remaining two guns were placed on the upper deck as chase guns.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] They fired a 44.9-kilogram (99.0 lb) shell at a muzzle velocity of only 322 metres per second (1,060 ft/s) and proved to be ineffective against armour.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] They were replaced by rifled breech-loading Modèle 1864 guns in 1868.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] Six 240-millimetre (9.4 in) guns were mounted in the centre of the gun deck and a pair of 194-millimetre (7.6 in) guns replaced the original chase guns.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] Named after the province of Normandy, *Normandie* was ordered around September 1858, six months after her sisters.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The ship was laid down at the Arsenal de Cherbourg on 14 September 1858, launched on 10 March 1860 and completed on 13 May 1862.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] In July 1862, *Normandie* became the first ironclad to cross the Atlantic, as the flagship of Vice Admiral Edmond Jurien de La Gravière, on her way to support the French intervention in Mexico.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] She was forced to return in April 1863 due to an outbreak of yellow fever that killed her captain, among others.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] While assigned to the Mediterranean Fleet, the ship made a port visit in August 1865 to Brest where the fleet hosted the British Channel Fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] A few days later the French fleet made a reciprocal visit to Portsmouth where it was hosted by the Channel Fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] From 1865 to 1868, *Normandie* was assigned to the Evolutionary Squadron where she was commanded by Bernard Jauréguiberry, among others.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] The ship was assigned to the ironclad squadron commanded by Rear Admiral Didelot during the Franco-Prussian War, but saw no action.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] Built of unseasoned timber, *Normandie* was in poor shape after the war and was decommissioned on 17 June 1871.
[src:french-ironclad-normandie/french-ironclad-normandie] Condemned on 1 August, the ship was subsequently broken up and her engine was installed in the breastwork monitor *Tonnerre*.
